Information-Theoretic Control of Partially Observable Biological Neural Networks for Organoid Intelligence

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

Abstract

The exponential growth of computational demands in artificial intelligence has exposed the fundamental energy inefficiency of silicon-based architectures, motivating the search for alternative paradigms. Organoid intelligence—the interfacing of lab-grown brain organoids with microelectrode arrays for biocomputing—has emerged as a promising direction, demonstrating remarkable energy efficiency and adaptive learning capabilities. However, current approaches remain largely empirical, lacking a rigorous mathematical foundation that accounts for the inherent complexities of living systems: partial observability, non-stationary dynamics, coarse actuation, and metabolic constraints. This thesis develops a comprehensive mathematical framework that transforms organoid intelligence from a biological curiosity into a formal computational architecture. The framework integrates four core components: (i) a non-stationary reservoir computing model that maintains a local echo state property despite continuous synaptic drift, (ii) an information-theoretic synaptic plasticity rule derived from the information bottleneck principle and constrained by metabolic homeostasis, (iii) a symbolic regression methodology with physics-informed priors to discover interpretable population-level dynamics, and (iv) a hardware-aware optimal control framework that respects the spatial aliasing constraints of multielectrode arrays and the stochastic nature of neural activity. A central innovation is the bio-digital twin architecture—a parallel shadow reservoir that continuously synchronizes with the physical organoid, enabling predictive gating of stimulation protocols to prevent over-stimulation and metabolic stress. Ethical considerations are formalized through a metabolic constraint on information and an integrated information monitor that automatically decoheres stimulation when complexity thresholds are exceeded. The framework yields testable predictions and a phased validation roadmap, positioning organoid intelligence as a sustainable, adaptive, and ethically governed alternative to conventional computing.

Introduction

The past decade has witnessed an unprecedented surge in the computational capabilities of artificial intelligence, driven largely by the scaling of deep neural networks on silicon hardware. Yet this progress has come at a steep energy cost: training a single large language model can consume as much electricity as a small city, and inference on deployed models requires datacenters that collectively contribute significantly to global carbon emissions. The fundamental physics of complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor (CMOS) technology imposes a lower bound on energy per operation, and as Moore's law slows, the search for alternative computing paradigms has intensified.

Biological neural networks offer a compelling alternative. The human brain performs complex cognitive tasks while consuming approximately 20 watts—orders of magnitude less than any electronic supercomputer. This efficiency stems from principles fundamentally different from digital computation: analog processing, massively parallel architecture, event-driven communication via spikes, and synaptic plasticity that enables learning from few examples. Recent advances in stem cell technology have made it possible to culture three-dimensional brain organoids—self-organizing clusters of functional neurons that recapitulate aspects of human brain development and activity. When interfaced with multielectrode arrays (MEAs), these organoids can be stimulated and recorded, creating a living computational substrate.

Early demonstrations of organoid intelligence are striking. The Brainoware architecture achieved approximately 78% accuracy in speech recognition tasks by treating an organoid as an adaptive reservoir. FinalSpark's Neuroplatform provides remote access to sixteen organoids for biocomputing experiments. Cortical Labs has shown that in vitro neurons can learn to play simplified games when embodied in a simulated environment. These proof-of-concept experiments hint at a future where biological and silicon systems collaborate, with organoids handling tasks that require rapid adaptation and energy-efficient pattern recognition.

However, the field remains in its infancy, and the gap between experimental demonstrations and a mature computing technology is vast. Current approaches treat the organoid largely as a black box, applying stimulation protocols based on heuristic intuition and recording outputs without a deep understanding of the underlying dynamics. To progress from empirical tinkering to principled engineering, a rigorous mathematical foundation is essential. This thesis aims to provide such a foundation, addressing the fundamental challenges that arise when biological systems are repurposed for computation.

The core challenges are fourfold. First, organoids are only partially observable: multielectrode arrays record from a tiny fraction of neurons, typically those near the electrode surface, leaving the vast majority of neural activity hidden. Any mathematical framework must contend with this fundamental uncertainty. Second, biological systems are inherently non-stationary. Synaptogenesis, pruning, metabolic fluctuations, and even cell death continuously alter the functional connectivity of the organoid. The assumption of fixed dynamics, common in reservoir computing, is violated. Third, actuation is coarse: electrical stimulation through an electrode activates thousands of neurons nonspecifically, and can trigger population bursts that overwhelm fine-grained control. Fourth, the organoid is a living system with metabolic needs and ethical considerations. Stimulation protocols that would be innocuous for silicon can cause excitotoxicity, metabolic stress, or—in speculative but serious ethical discussions—potentially contribute to the emergence of sentient-like states. Any framework for organoid intelligence must incorporate these constraints as first-class elements.

This thesis develops a mathematical framework that confronts these challenges directly. The framework is built on four pillars:

1. Non-stationary reservoir computing. We model the organoid as a slow-fast dynamical system in which fast neural activity evolves on top of slowly drifting connectivity. A local echo state property is defined and sufficient conditions derived, ensuring that computational stability is maintained despite continuous drift.
2. Information-theoretic synaptic plasticity. The information bottleneck principle is extended to spiking neurons with metabolic constraints, yielding a three-factor learning rule that balances task-relevant information against energy consumption. We prove that under timescale separation, this rule converges to fixed points that minimize an effective free energy.
3. Physics-informed symbolic regression. To discover interpretable models of organoid dynamics, we employ sparse identification of nonlinear dynamics (SINDy) augmented with thermodynamic priors—specifically, the fluctuation-dissipation theorem—ensuring that discovered equations respect fundamental physical constraints and do not describe unphysical "perpetual motion" neural activity.
4. Hardware-aware optimal control. The neural compiler that translates tasks to stimulation patterns explicitly models the low-rank actuation imposed by MEA physics, incorporates population burst noise, and uses stochastic adjoint methods to produce controls robust to neural variability.

A central innovation is the bio-digital twin: a parallel shadow reservoir that continuously synchronizes with the physical organoid through Bayesian inference. Before any stimulation is applied to the living tissue, its effect is simulated on the digital twin. If predicted performance degrades or safety metrics are violated, the protocol is rejected and a re-synchronization phase initiated. This predictive gating prevents over-stimulation and metabolic stress, effectively making the digital twin a guardian of both computational performance and biological well-being.

Ethical considerations are not treated as an afterthought but integrated directly into the mathematical formalism. A metabolic constraint on information defines permissible stimulation regimes in terms of firing rates and their derivatives, providing a quantitative boundary between healthy operation and excitotoxicity. An integrated information monitor computes a real-time approximation of Φ (a measure of information integration) and automatically decoheres stimulation if complexity exceeds a threshold calibrated from comparative neurobiology. This serves as an information-theoretic anesthetic, ensuring that the organoid never enters a state that could plausibly be associated with suffering.

The framework yields a set of testable predictions and a phased validation roadmap. In silico experiments with simulated spiking networks will verify the local echo state property and the convergence of plasticity. Hybrid validation using public organoid datasets will demonstrate the efficacy of the bio-digital twin and the safety monitors. Finally, closed-loop pilot studies on live cultures will measure the total cost of computation—a metric that includes both inference energy and the metabolic maintenance energy of the idle organoid—providing an honest comparison with silicon alternatives.

Thesis outline. Chapter 2 introduces the non-stationary reservoir model, defines the local echo state property, and derives adaptive spectral radius estimation. Chapter 3 develops the information-theoretic plasticity rule with homeostatic regulation and proves convergence. Chapter 4 presents physics-informed symbolic regression for population-level dynamics, incorporating fluctuation-dissipation constraints. Chapter 5 formulates hardware-aware optimal control with rank-constrained actuation and stochastic adjoint methods. Chapter 6 details the bio-digital twin architecture, including predictive gating and ensemble Kalman filtering for synchronization. Chapter 7 formalizes ethical constraints as information-theoretic bounds and integrated information monitoring. Chapter 8 outlines the validation roadmap, with specific metrics and experimental protocols. Chapter 9 concludes with a discussion of implications and future directions.

This thesis aspires to lay the mathematical groundwork for a new paradigm of computing—one that harnesses the extraordinary efficiency and adaptability of biological neurons while respecting the fundamental constraints and ethical responsibilities that come with manipulating living systems. The result is a framework that transforms organoid intelligence from a promising experiment into a principled engineering discipline.


